  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Connecticut federal contract obligations for FY2026 to date total $14.5B across 19,289 awards, with an average award size of $750K. Obligations are down 58.8% year over year. The Department of Defense accounts for the vast majority of spending at $14.2B, while the next-highest buying agencies, Department of Veterans Affairs and Department of Homeland Security, account for $105M and $102M respectively. Top contractors include ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION at $8.3B, RTX CORPORATION at $3B, and SIKORSKY AIRCRAFT CORPORATION at $2.3B. Engineering Services is the largest industry by obligations at $6.8B, followed by Aircraft Manufacturing at $2.6B and Ship Building and Repairing at $1.5B. FY obligations have varied in recent years, with FY21 at $18.4B, FY22 at $22.3B, FY23 at $26B, FY24 at $20B, FY25 at $35.1B, and FY26 to date at $14.5B. All figures are contract obligations; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How concentrated is federal buying in Connecticut?",
        "body": "Federal buying in Connecticut is highly concentrated: the Department of Defense accounts for $14.2B of the $14.5B in obligations for FY2026 to date. The next nine agencies each account for amounts at or below $105M, with the Department of Veterans Affairs at $105M and the Department of Homeland Security at $102M. That agency concentration corresponds with large awards to specific vendors in the state."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which industries and vendors dominate Connecticut obligations?",
        "body": "Engineering Services leads industries with $6.8B in obligations, followed by Aircraft Manufacturing at $2.6B and Ship Building and Repairing at $1.5B. Major vendors include ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION at $8.3B, RTX CORPORATION at $3B, and SIKORSKY AIRCRAFT CORPORATION at $2.3B. Several aerospace and defense-related NAICS categories together represent a large share of the state's obligations."
      }
    ]
  },
